<DOC><DOCNO> AP900831-0170 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-31-90 2317EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Gulf-Radio     08-31 0194</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Gulf-Radio,190</SECOND><HEAD>Voice of America to Broadcast Around the Clock to Gulf</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Voice of America will beginaround-the-clock broadcasts to the Middle East next week, despiteIraqi efforts to jam the programming, the government announcedFriday.   The broadcasting service, an arm of the government's UnitedStates Information Agency, is already beaming 9 3@4 hours daily ofbroadcasting in Arabic to the region.   Beginning Wednesday at 7 a.m. EDT, that will increase to 13hours a day. The remaining 11 hours of programming each day will bein English.   ``In times of crisis we redouble our efforts to pierce theinformation barriers surrounding closed societies,'' Voice ofAmerica Director Richard W. Carlson said.   Iraq is jamming Voice of America broadcasts to the Persian Gulfwith 500-kilowatt transmitters.   To get its programming through, the Voice of America has beensending its radio signals over short- and medium-wave frequencies,varying them in an effort to evade the Iraqi jamming. It is alsosending audio signals that can be picked up by satellite dishes.   The agency is beaming news programming, as well as StateDepartment advisories meant for Americans in Iraq and Kuwait.</TEXT></DOC>